Configuration file format for nat_ambio_surround (natambio)
================================================================================

natambio is configured by a single XML file passed on the command line. Lines
that should be ignored can be wrapped in standard XML comments (<!-- ... -->).
Tag content with leading/trailing whitespace is taken as-is.

This document describes the schema as accepted by the parser in src/naconf.cpp.
Tags not listed here are silently ignored. Several example configurations live
under the tests/ and sample_configs/ directory.


Document structure
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The parser scans for the first <natambio> element either as the root element
or as a direct child of the root element. Everything outside <natambio> is
ignored. A typical wrapper looks like:

    <main>
      <natambio>
        ... blocks below ...
      </natambio>
    </main>

Inside <natambio> the following top-level blocks are recognised, in any order:

    <coeff>        one convolution coefficient set (from a file or derived
                   from the convolution of other coeffs)
    <race>         a RACE crosstalk-cancellation filter generator that
                   synthesises a pair of coeffs (direct + cross)
    <low_and_high_filter>
                   a crossover filter generator that synthesises a
                   complementary low-pass / high-pass coeff pair
    <loudness>     an equal-loudness compensation filter generator that
                   synthesises a single minimum-phase coeff
    <convol>       one convolution routing channel
    <panambio>     one PCA spatial-decomposition engine
    <jack_input>   JACK client name and input ports
    <jack_output>  JACK output ports

<coeff>, <race>, <low_and_high_filter>, <loudness>, <convol> and <panambio>
may appear any number of times.
<jack_input> and <jack_output> should appear once each.


Sample rate
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
There is no global sample-rate tag. Before parsing the configuration, natambio
opens a minimal short-lived JACK client to read the running server's sample
rate, and uses it for everything:

  - the <race>, <low_and_high_filter> and <loudness> blocks generate their
    filters at that rate (so they take no <sample_rate> tag), and
  - every <coeff> loaded from a <filename> is checked against it; a file whose
    sample rate differs aborts the program with an error.

JACK must therefore be running before natambio is started.


Gain convention
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
`<attenuation>` fields (in <coeff>, <convol> and <low_and_high_filter>) are
expressed in dB of *attenuation*, converted internally via `pow(10, -dB/20)`:

    positive value  -> attenuation (quieter)
    negative value  -> amplification (louder)
    0               -> unity

The Panambio gain fields (<main_gain>, <ambience_gain>, <surround_gain>) use the
OPPOSITE sign -- a plain dB gain converted via `pow(10, dB/20)`:

    positive value  -> amplification (louder)
    negative value  -> attenuation (quieter)
    0               -> unity

For the Panambio gain fields, omitting the value for the active mode is a parse
error (an unset gain cannot be told apart from 0 dB internally).


<coeff> -- convolution coefficient set
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A coeff holds one set of convolution coefficients. It is obtained in one of two
ways:

  (a) loaded from an audio file (<filename>), or
  (b) derived from the convolution of other coeffs (one or more <convol_coeff>).

All <coeff> blocks must appear before any <convol> that references them, and a
derived coeff must appear after all the coeffs it references (convol_coeffs are
resolved in document order, after the whole file has been read).

(a) File-loaded coeff
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Loads one channel from an audio file (any libsndfile-supported format).

    <coeff>
      <name>direct left</name>
      <filename>~/IR/direct_left.wav</filename>
      <channel>1</channel>
      <skip>0</skip>
      <length>8192</length>
      <attenuation>0.0</attenuation>
    </coeff>

    name         Unique identifier referenced by <convol>/<coeff_name>.       (required)
    filename     Path to the audio file. `~` expands to $HOME.                 (required unless
                                                                                <convol_coeff> is used)
    channel      1-based channel index to read.                                (optional, default 1)
    skip         Frames to skip at the start of the file.                      (optional, default 0)
    length       Frames to read. When omitted (or 0) the whole file is read    (optional, default:
                 and length is set to the file's total frame count, or that     whole file)
                 count minus <skip> when leading frames are skipped.
    attenuation  Per-coefficient gain in dB attenuation.                       (optional, default 0)

The file's sample rate must equal the JACK sample rate. natambio probes the
running JACK server's sample rate at start-up (before parsing) and checks every
loaded file against it; a mismatch aborts with an error.

(b) Derived (convolved) coeff
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
When one or more <convol_coeff> tags are present, <filename> is ignored and the
coeff is built, after the whole config is parsed, by convolving the referenced
coeffs together (left to right):

    <coeff>
      <name>RACE EQ direct left</name>
      <convol_coeff>RACE direct</convol_coeff>   <!-- convolved with... -->
      <convol_coeff>DRC EQ left</convol_coeff>   <!-- ...this one        -->
      <length>16384</length>
    </coeff>

    name         Unique identifier referenced by <convol>/<coeff_name>.       (required)
    convol_coeff Name of another <coeff> to convolve. Repeatable (1..n).      (>= 1)
    length       Output length in samples. The convolution result is          (optional, default:
                 truncated (or zero-padded) to this length; 0/omitted keeps    full convolution
                 the full linear-convolution length.                           length)
    attenuation  Extra gain in dB attenuation applied to the result.          (optional, default 0)

With a single <convol_coeff> the referenced coeff is copied (truncated/padded to
<length>); with several they are convolved in sequence. The convolution is a
single-precision FFT convolution (the fft_convolve_truncate routine in src/dsp.c).

When <length> is omitted the derived coeff is set to the full linear-convolution
length, i.e. the sum of the referenced coeffs' lengths minus (count - 1). This
is computed while parsing when every referenced coeff is already declared;
references to coeffs generated later (<race>, <low_and_high_filter>, <loudness>)
are instead resolved when the convolutions are built.

All referenced coeffs must share the same sample rate; the derived coeff
inherits it. As with file-loaded coeffs, that sample rate must equal the JACK
sample rate.

Referenced coeffs may themselves be derived coeffs, as long as they are declared
earlier in the file.

Special name: a <convol> that references `<coeff_name>delta</coeff_name>`
activates bypass mode (no convolution; only the convol's delay and
attenuation are applied to the mixed input).


<race> -- RACE crosstalk-cancellation filter generator
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A <race> block synthesises, from scratch, a pair of FIR filters implementing
the RACE (Recursive Ambiophonic Crosstalk Elimination) recursion combined with
a van Opstal ILD model. It produces two coeffs -- a direct-path filter and a
cross-path filter -- that are added to the coeff list under the names given by
<direct_filter_name> / <cross_filter_name>, exactly as if they had been loaded
from a file. They can then be referenced by <convol>/<coeff_name> (see the
four <convol> blocks in sample_configs/race_sample_02.xml) or even by a derived
coeff's <convol_coeff>.

    <race>
      <itd_us>180</itd_us>
      <ild_db>20.5</ild_db>
      <ild_alpha>1.8</ild_alpha>
      <azimuth_deg>20</azimuth_deg>
      <length>4096</length>
      <direct_filter_name>RACE direct</direct_filter_name>
      <cross_filter_name>RACE cross</cross_filter_name>
    </race>

    itd_us              Inter-aural time difference, microseconds. Converted   (optional, default 0)
                        to the RACE recursion delay using the JACK sample rate.
    ild_db              Inter-aural level difference per recursion step, in dB  (optional, default 0)
                        of attenuation.
    ild_alpha           van Opstal ILD model scale factor.                     (optional, default 0)
    azimuth_deg         Source azimuth, degrees, fed to the ILD model.         (optional, default 0)
    length              Length of each generated filter, in samples.           (required, > 0)
    direct_filter_name  Name of the resulting direct-path coeff.               (required)
    cross_filter_name   Name of the resulting cross-path coeff.                (required)

The two generated coeffs are created at the JACK sample rate (see "Sample rate"
above; there is no <sample_rate> tag). The filter names must not collide with
any other coeff name. RACE coeffs are generated after all <coeff> blocks have
been read, so a derived coeff may convolve them via <convol_coeff>.


<low_and_high_filter> -- complementary crossover filter generator
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A <low_and_high_filter> block synthesises, from scratch, a complementary pair of
FIR filters that split a signal at a crossover frequency: a low-pass and a
high-pass. It produces two coeffs added to the coeff list under the names given
by <low_pass_coeff_name> / <high_pass_coeff_name>, exactly as if they had been
loaded from a file. They can then be referenced by <convol>/<coeff_name> (see
the four <convol> blocks in sample_configs/subwoofer_sample.xml -- a typical
subwoofer / satellite split) or by a derived coeff's <convol_coeff>.

    <low_and_high_filter>
      <frequency>100.0</frequency>
      <dB_octave>24</dB_octave>
      <attenuation>0</attenuation>
      <length>8192</length>
      <low_pass_coeff_name>Low pass FIR</low_pass_coeff_name>
      <high_pass_coeff_name>High pass FIR</high_pass_coeff_name>
    </low_and_high_filter>

    frequency             Crossover (cut-off) frequency, Hz.                 (required, > 0)
    dB_octave             Low-pass roll-off slope above the crossover, in    (optional, default 0)
                          dB per octave.
    attenuation           Pass-band attenuation applied to both filters, dB. (optional, default 0)
    length                Length of each generated filter, in samples.       (required, > 0)
    low_pass_coeff_name   Name of the resulting low-pass coeff.              (required)
    high_pass_coeff_name  Name of the resulting high-pass coeff.             (required)

The low-pass is designed with firwin2 (a flat pass-band at -attenuation dB up to
<frequency>, then a constant <dB_octave> dB/octave roll-off). The high-pass is
its exact complement -- an attenuation-adjusted linear-phase delta minus the
low-pass -- so that the two filters sum back to an (attenuated) delta. Both are
then converted to minimum phase, and those minimum-phase filters are what get
applied.

The two generated coeffs are created at the JACK sample rate (see "Sample rate"
above; there is no <sample_rate> tag). The filter names must not collide with
any other coeff name. They are generated after all <coeff> blocks have been
read, so a derived coeff may convolve them via <convol_coeff>.


<loudness> -- equal-loudness compensation filter generator
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A <loudness> block synthesises a single FIR filter that follows an equal-loudness
(isophonic) contour. It produces one coeff -- added to the coeff list under the
name given by <filter_name> -- whose magnitude is the DIFFERENCE between the
chosen model's contour at <phon> and its contour at <ref_phon> (each contour
normalised to 0 dB at 1 kHz). The result is a "playback at <phon>, mastered for
<ref_phon>" loudness compensation curve: it is flat (0 dB) at 1 kHz and boosts
the low (and high) frequencies when <phon> is below <ref_phon>. The coeff is
minimum phase.

    <loudness>
      <phon>70</phon>
      <ref_phon>90</ref_phon>
      <model>fletcher-munson</model>
      <length>4096</length>
      <filter_name>loudness filter</filter_name>
    </loudness>

    phon         Target listening level, phon.                              (required)
    ref_phon     Reference (mastering) level, phon; subtracted from the     (required)
                 target contour.
    model        Equal-loudness model. One of:                              (required)
                   iso226-2003, iso226-2023  (analytic ISO 226 formula)
                   fletcher-munson           (tabulated 1933 curves)
                   a-weighting, b-weighting, c-weighting
                                             (IEC weightings; these ignore
                                              phon, so the difference curve is
                                              flat and the filter is a unit
                                              impulse)
                 (robinson-dadson is not implemented.)
    length       Length of the generated filter, in samples.                (required, > 0)
    filter_name  Name of the resulting coeff.                               (required)

The contour difference is sampled by firwin2 (a flat-at-1 kHz target curve,
log-interpolated/extrapolated from the model's tabulated points, rolling off to
silence outside 10 Hz - 20 kHz) and the resulting linear-phase filter is
converted to minimum phase. The generated coeff is created at the JACK sample
rate (see "Sample rate" above; there is no <sample_rate> tag). Its name must not
collide with any other coeff name. It is generated after all <coeff> blocks have
been read, so a derived coeff may convolve it via <convol_coeff> (see
sample_configs/drc_eq_loudness_sample.xml, which convolves it with a DRC EQ
filter).


<jack_input> -- JACK client name and input ports
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    <jack_input>
      <clientname>natambio</clientname>
      <port>
        <name>input_left</name>
        <destname>system:capture_1</destname>
      </port>
      <port>
        <name>input_right</name>
        <destname>system:capture_2</destname>
      </port>
    </jack_input>

    clientname   JACK client name. Default: "natambio".                        (optional, one tag)
    port         JACK input port definition. May appear multiple times.        (>= 1 required)
      name       Port name (as seen on the JACK graph).                        (required)
      destname   External port to auto-connect on startup.                     (optional)


<jack_output> -- JACK output ports
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    <jack_output>
      <port>
        <name>output_left</name>
        <destname>system:playback_1</destname>
      </port>
      ...
    </jack_output>

    port         JACK output port definition. May appear multiple times.       (>= 1 required)
      name       Port name.                                                    (required)
      destname   External port to auto-connect on startup.                     (optional)


<panambio> -- PCA spatial decomposition
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Each <panambio> block defines ONE Panambio engine. Use multiple <panambio>
blocks for multiple engines.

    <panambio>
      <name>front stereo</name>
      <mode>front</mode>
      <steps_length>3</steps_length>
      <main_gain>-2.0</main_gain>
      <ambience_gain>2.0</ambience_gain>
      <input_left>input_left</input_left>
      <input_right>input_right</input_right>
      <output_left>pn_output_left</output_left>
      <output_right>pn_output_right</output_right>
    </panambio>

    name             Label for diagnostics.                                    (optional)
    mode             "front" or "rear".                                        (required)
    steps_length     PCA analysis window length, in JACK buffer periods.       (required, >= 0)
    main_gain        Main-component gain, dB (positive = amplification;        (required for front)
                     see Gain convention). (front mode only)
    ambience_gain    Ambience-component gain, dB (positive = amplification).   (required for front)
                     (front mode only)
    surround_gain    Surround-component gain, dB (positive = amplification).   (required for rear)
                     (rear mode only)
    input_left       Source JACK input port for the left channel.              (required)
    input_right      Source JACK input port for the right channel.             (required)
    output_left      Left output: a <jack_output>/<port>/<name>, or a          (required, or
                     virtual name consumed by <convol>/<from_panambio>.         mid/side equivalent)
    output_right     Right output (same resolution as output_left).            (required, or
                                                                                mid/side equivalent)
    mid_output_left, mid_output_right
    side_output_left, side_output_right
                     Optional separate outputs for the mid/side intermediate
                     signals (same name resolution as output_left/right).      (optional)

Mode semantics:
    front: writes main component to *output_left/right channels, ambience
           is mixed in via the ambience_gain.
    rear : writes surround signal to *output_left/right channels using
           inter-channel correlation to distinguish centred from decorrelated
           content.

Port name resolution: when <output_left> / <output_right> / mid_* / side_*
match a <jack_output>/<port>/<name>, the signal is written directly to that
JACK output port. Otherwise the name acts as a virtual buffer that <convol>
blocks can pick up via <from_panambio>.

See sample_configs/panambio_process.xml for a full example: a front engine
routed through its mid/side outputs and a rear engine through plain left/right
outputs.


<convol> -- convolution routing channel
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Each <convol> defines one channel through the convolution engine. Inputs from
multiple sources are summed before convolution; outputs may fan out to several
sinks. There may be up to 64 <convol> blocks (zita-convolver hard limit).

    <convol>
      <name>direct left</name>
      <coeff_name>direct left</coeff_name>
      <from_input>input_left</from_input>
      <from_panambio>pn_output_left</from_panambio>
      <from_convol>some other convolver</from_convol>
      <to_output>output_left</to_output>
      <attenuation>5.0</attenuation>
      <delay>0</delay>
    </convol>

    name           Unique identifier; targeted by other convolvers'           (required)
                   <from_convol>.
    coeff_name     Reference to a <coeff>/<name>, or "delta" for bypass.      (required)
    from_input     Mix in a <jack_input>/<port>/<name>. Repeatable.           (>= 0)
    from_panambio  Mix in a Panambio virtual output (left/right/mid/side).    (>= 0)
                   Repeatable.
    from_convol    Mix in another <convol>'s output by name. Repeatable.      (>= 0)
    to_output      Send convolver output to a <jack_output>/<port>/<name>.    (>= 0)
                   Repeatable. A convol with no <to_output> is intermediate-
                   only and feeds other convolvers via <from_convol>.
    attenuation    Output gain in dB attenuation.                              (optional, default 0)
    delay          Output delay in samples (sample-accurate ring buffer).      (optional, default 0)

Care must be taken not to create convolution loops with chained <from_convol>
references.


Notes
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 - The example XML files under tests/ are kept for reference but may use
   tag names from earlier schema revisions (e.g. nested <pca> blocks inside
   <panambio>, or <left_channel>/<right_channel>). The schema above
   reflects what the current parser in src/naconf.cpp accepts; tags it does
   not recognise are silently ignored, which can mask configuration errors.
 - An extended developer-oriented description of the program architecture
   (not the file format) lives in src/README.md.
